I'm sorry to those few people that follow me and enjoy my toots and engagement, but it seems when I try to engage in a lighthearted way, I get insulted. It's not quite fun and is destroying my mental health. This will probably be my last toot for awhile.

Do better.

I think that one of the things that makes me dream irresponsibly about establishing a commune is the idea of following your pursuits without the chain of capitalism guiding your efforts to profit rather than improvement.

The area I think a lot about this is in architecture where its intersection with reducing construction costs often dilutes creativity, which then inhibits innovation.

I really furrow my brow at the common argument that capitalism spurs innovation, for various reasons. If you look at history before the industrial revolution, that notion would be demonstrably false. Rather, capitalism mostly just spurs *technology* as a building block from our previous discoveries for profit, often in the process erasing the discoveries that led to innovation (see: the lost artisanship of proven construction techniques for more modern, cheaper, faster, unsustainable, and often toxic substitutes).

Many technological advances at the dawn of capitalism were to improve productivity, usually at the detriment of labour's well-being. So many early machines and factories were places where lives and limbs went missing. True innovation in these circumstances were for safeguarding, not production itself.

No one widely safeguards livestock in industrial farming, for example, with people having been treated similarly, even today.

As capitalism moved along, what we label as ‚Äúadvances‚Äù were often times capital just needing something new to produce, to create a false need and convince us we can't live without it, especially post-war.

And, many of out technological advances came from one of capital's best friends: war.

After 400+ years of capitalism making the argument, we seem to have forgotten that, in the before times, we made discoveries because we cared to learn observe, not profiteer.

I just don't buy capitalism's argument. The wheel wasn't invented for shareholders to mass produce.

There are studies on the idea of humanity's intrinsic motivation, which tend to die before full completion because, uh, reasons.

Truthfully, I just want to make things better just because, not because I could profit from it.

Then back to the idea of the commune: if the group had needs met, regardless of education levels, I think you'd see problems innovatively resolved to the group's needs. With more free time and resources, I think you'd see higher levels of ingenuity simply because people want to learn things and apply them, especially if they benefit the group

But, the conditions in small groups are daunting. This would be much more plausible in larger groups dozens, hundreds, or even thousands of people.

Attempted a #dicefail experiment tonight. I used a technique I learned from a YouTuber doing resin art:

I put a bit of UV resin at the bottom of the mold, maybe 1/4 full, and then laid a piece of a vinyl glove on top, then carefully scootched it around with the end of a paintbrush.

I let that cure, then pulled out the vinyl and painted on a thin layer of resin mixed with purple mica. I cured *that*, and then filled the mold and did the rest of the die.

The result is promising! the weird, uneven surface in the middle of the die ends up looking like swirls and tendrils when painted with color. I might experiment with actual paint, darker mica, or a thicker layer, but overall I think this is worth trying with epoxy resin! Finicky as all get out to get the vinyl in there without trappinf air bubbles tho...

Ireland thanks Johansson for this regulator, says they're a strong supporter. Wants to agree on file before end of legislative term.

Cyprus welcomes the Commissions proposal. Wants to keep voluntary detection.

France also wants to keep voluntary detection, says it'll be an effective tool.

Estonia doubts the necessity of the initiative, says it is important necessary to protect children E2EE communication from backdoors.

Latvia: Thanks for commission report, wants to step forward without doubt, hopes for success of partial general approach in coming weeks, agrees with Irish position.

Germany: Thanks presidency, Johansson. Agrees with France, need to ensure voluntary detection. Says changes are necessary for encrypted communication, focus on vicitims, add perspective.

Bulgaria: Supports Irelands position, wants widest possible scope of the regulation.

"Seven years ago, Redonda, a volcanic island in the Caribbean Sea, resembled the moon‚Äôs surface: a dusty, debris-covered, barren terrain.

The island, which is part of Antigua and Barbuda, had once been mined for guano, seabird excrement used for fertiliser. However, mining operations on Redonda ceased around the start of the first world war, and when the miners were gone, they left behind a legacy of rats and goats.

Over the successive decades, the rats and goats stripped Redonda of its vegetation. Rocks and soil slid into the sea, damaging the reefs and seagrass and making it dangerous for anyone to venture on to the island.

Then, in 2016, conservationists began removing the rats and goats to restore the island. They first used a rodenticide to eliminate the rats while not harming other biodiversity.

The one and only thing I miss about Twitter is the small but vigorous community of Gateshead fans there. Been reminded of that because our beloved Mike Williamson has left, gone to take over at Milton Keynes.

It was always bound to happen, sooner or later, that he'd be picked up by a bigger club. He's done far far too well to stay at little old Gateshead.

It's not just how well he's done, though, which makes this a sad time. He joined as a player when the club was in the process of very nearly being killed off by an appalling owner. He stuck around when there was no reason for him to do so, agreed to become manager when we'd been forcibly relegated and had literally no players other than himself, a few days before the season started.

And from that it's been success after success and all with a very entertaining style and a thoroughly decent spirit. Damn, I'm going to miss the big guy.

Someone, please tell me I'm not crazy and windows 10 and possibly others have a built-in limiter you cannot disable, which automatically engages when 32 bit float audio reaches above 0 db fs. This, interestingly enough applies to both wave audio and ogg vorbis encoded audio, since ogg vorbis has no concept of bit depth and audio is always encoded as 32 bit float. Guess you learn something new every day...

It doesn't matter which program you use to play this file, it will violently bring down the entire windows volume. Yes, including nvda.

As far as I know there is no bloody way to turn off this daft thing but to use something else that isn't wasapi.

Try the same thing in linux for example with mpv and you'll hear the actual clipping.

Windows on the other hand, will make you believe everything is absolutely fine.

How the hell am I supposed to realize I need to lower the gain of this thing if I can never hear it clipping?

Sometimes, I really hate windows.
